inctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Helene","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Helen  , now in fairly frequent use in the English-speaking world, usually without the accents."],"variants":[{"name":"Helena","meanings":["form of   Helen  , used also in Germany, the Netherlands, Scandinavia, and Eastern Europe."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Helene de Saint Sauveur was born in 1022, in Avranches, Normandy, France. She had at least 2 daughters with Robert le Bigod. She died in 1035, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 13."},"et":{"1022–1035":"1022–1035","1015–1071":"1015–1071","1053–1085":"1053–1085","1055–1107":"1055–1107","1107":"1107","1015":"1015","1035":"1035","1022":"1022","1055":"1055","1053"